Description: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a small area with the impression of wood, probably from a bolt or a box knob, perpendicular to this two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.2 cm. The front side is flat running down towards the edges, covered with finger impressions and shows part of an oval seal with a circumferential line. The motif shows hieroglyphs, originally arranged in three horizontal lines from which parts of the middle and lower line are preserved. Visible is a seated figure at the left, facing to the right, next to it a khpr, in the lowest row the signs are not recognisable anymore.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
